<HL>
   Honeywell Seeks
   A Halt of Imports
   Of Minolta Product
   ----
   By Eduardo Lachica
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   HON J.MNO
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Honeywell Inc. petitioned the International
Trade Commission to halt imports of Minolta cameras with
automatic-focusing devices, charging that these products
infringe Honeywell patents.
   Honeywell's action is a surprising departure from its
earlier advocacy of harmonious relations with Japan. But
Christopher Steffen, Honeywell's vice president and chief
financial officer, said that seeking the ITC action is one of
the few alternatives left for Honeywell to recover "hundreds
of millions of dollars in lost royalties" for its pioneering
work on auto-focusing technology.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ITC petition brings further pressure on Minolta Camera
Co., the Japanese maker, to settle Honeywell's separate civil
suit seeking damages for alleged patent infringement, misuse
of trade secrets and breach of contract. The case has been
dragging on for nearly three years in a New Jersey district
court.
   In the suit, Honeywell claims that it confidentially
provided Minolta with information for making auto-focus
modules with the understanding that the Osaka manufacturer
would later incorporate Honeywell-made ones in its cameras.
The suit also charges that while absorbing this know-how
Minolta secretly conducted its own parallel development
effort and, in 1985, introduced products using modules based
on Honeywell technology.
   If the ITC accepts the petition, Honeywell could win
relief in 12 months. Honeywell doesn't expect the New Jersey
suit to go to trial until 1992.
   An ITC ruling favoring Honeywell would be a severe blow to
Minolta. The Japanese company's popular Maxxum models, which
feature the disputed devices, account for much of its $1
billion in annual camera sales world-wide. Moreover, the
trade impact could be even broader if Honeywell takes action
against 15 other Japanese camera makers that allegedly
obtained the same technology under similar confidential
arrangements. Honeywell said these firms include Canon Inc.,
Asahi Optical Co., Nippon Kokaku K.K. and Olympus Optical Co.
   Minolta dismissed Honeywell's charges as "baseless,"
claiming that they ignore an earlier history of development
in auto-focus cameras, including "significant breakthroughs"
by Minolta. "As we have argued in federal court -- the proper
forum for this dispute -- we believe the Honeywell patents
claims in question are invalid and unenforceable," the
company said.
   "Honeywell, which does not make or sell cameras, is asking
the U.S. government to prevent Minolta -- and perhaps every
other major camera manufacturer in the world -- from selling
cameras in the U.S.," Minolta said. The company also charged
Honeywell with attempting to breach a 1988 agreement to
confine the dispute in the New Jersey court.
   Honeywell's complaint is likely to resonate in Washington
because of the Bush administration's concern about allegedly
unfair business practices of other Japanese companies.
Honeywell insists, though, that its problems with Minolta and
possibly with other Japanese camera makers are exceptions to
its otherwise productive dealings in Japan. "We've had
technology arrangements with other Japanese companies and
ended up with royalty agreements," Honeywell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0134
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0134.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Digital Says
   Profit Estimates
   Could be High
   ---
   Computer Firm Says Sales
   Are Soft In U.S., U.K.
   In Fiscal Fourth Quarter
   ----
   William M. Bulkeley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   DEC
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   MAYNARD, Mass. -- Digital Equipment Corp. told analysts
that earnings estimates for its fiscal fourth quarter ending
June 30 appear "too optimistic" because of soft sales in the
U.S. and the United Kingdom.
   The announcement led to a mild sell-off of Digital's often
volatile stock. The shares fell $1.75 to $86.375 in heavy New
York Stock Exchange composite trading of 1,171,700 shares.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Some analysts said the softness in the U.K. may presage
poor results for other computer companies as well since
European sales have been a bright spot for many large
computer companies.
   "I wouldn't be surprised to see some cuts in other stocks
before we're finished," with this quarter, said Stephen
Smith, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc.
   A Digital spokesman said most analysts had been
forecasting net income of $1.60 to $1.80 a share for the
fourth quarter compared with a year earlier when the company
earned $2.51 a share, on net income of $313.2 million. After
the announcement, analysts said they weren't sure how far to
cut their Digital estimates but some trimmed them to as low
as $1.25 a share.
   James M. Osterhoff, Digital's vice president-finance, told
a Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. conference that "our current
rate of profitability doesn't meet the expectations of our
investors -- or ourselves." He added: "The U.S. market
continues to be sluggish for us, and certain international
markets are experiencing softness, such as the U.K. where
high interest rates are cutting business expansion."
   Jay P. Stevens, an analyst with Dean Witter, said that
besides the economic problems in major markets Digital has
been caught in a bad product cycle. At the high end,
customers are awaiting deliveries of the VAX 9000, Digital's
first powerful mainframe computer. Although originally
expected early in the fourth quarter, Digital now says there
won't be any significant revenue from the VAX 9000 until
fiscal 1991. And many analysts don't expect much impact until
the second quarter of that year.
   In addition, Mr. Stevens said, sales of Digital's small
VAX 3000 computers, which had been strong earlier this year,
have weakened recently because customers expect Digital to
announce replacement products next month at its DECWorld
trade show. That weakness "is breaking the camel's back," he
said.
   Laura Conigliaro, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities, said investors hadn't been counting on a strong
fourth quarter for Digital and had been looking to 1991
instead. "If it had been a giant surprise the stock would
have come down 30%," she said.
   Nevertheless, some analysts cut their estimates for fiscal
1991 as well because they expect the economic problems to
reduce benefits from the new product cycle. Mr. Stevens said
he expects fiscal 1990 pershare earnings of about $4.10,
rising to $8.35 in fiscal 1991. PaineWebber's Mr. Smith
predicted fiscal 1991 net of about $7.50 a share.
   In fiscal 1989, net income was $1.07 billion, or $8.45 a
share, on revenue of $12.74 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0133
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0133.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   Bad Organization Ambushes Generals
   ----
   By Caspar W. Weinberger
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<LP>
   Why do good armies fail?
   This is the question the authors of "Military Misfortunes:
The Anatomy of Failure in War" (Macmillan/Free Press, 296
pages, $22.95) seek to answer by analyzing five campaigns
that resulted in notable defeats (and, of course, notable
victories for the other side).
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The failure of the British landing at Gallipoli designed
to break the stalemate on the Western Front in 1915; the
shocking shipping losses we suffered from German U-boats in
1942; the rout of our Eighth Army from its advanced positions
near the Yalu River in Korea in 1950; the surprise and defeat
of the Israelis in 1973; and the catastrophic collapse of the
French in 1940. These are the "lost victories" examined by
Eliot A. Cohen, a strategic analyst at Harvard's Olin
Institute, and John Gooch, a British professor of military
history.
   By misfortunes, the authors mean "failures attributable
neither to gross disproportions in odds nor to egregious
incompetence on the part of the victim nor yet to
extraordinary skill on the part of the victor." Indeed, in
all five instances, the forces seemed balanced in the
beginning. So what determined the outcome?
   Not surprisingly, Messrs. Cohen and Gooch did not find one
specific cause nor any particularly discernible common thread
fitting all five case histories. But they do single out one
principal culprit: poor military organization. In their view,
organizational failure often was more culpable than specific
decisions made during battle. Indeed, both authors reject
what they call the "Man in the Dock" theory and generally
absolve individual commanders from singlehandedly engineering
their defeats, even though some of their actions may have
been dismally inadequate.
   A good example is Gen. Ian Hamilton, commander at
Gallipoli. Once he failed to receive the corps commanders he
had wanted, Hamilton seems to have lacked the imagination to
rethink his options and further exacerbated the situation
with his hands-off approach to military command. A concept
well-established in the upper echelons of the British army,
it also was exemplified by Lt. Gen. Frederick Stopford, who
"commanded" the IX Corps at Suvla Bay by so remote a control
that he used small boats to communicate with his troops while
he remained at sea.
   Even Gen. Maurice-Gustave Gamelin, who commanded the
French forces in 1940 with such passive incompetence, escapes
total blame. Among other things, "captured intelligence
information was often transmitted too slowly up the chain of
command to have any operational effect," the authors suggest.
   So it comes as no particular surprise that Gen. Douglas
MacArthur is specifically absolved from responsibility for
the bloody defeats the Chinese inflicted on the United
Nations forces at Yalu River in 1950. The general often is
blamed for provoking the Chinese by advancing on the Yalu,
but the authors take a broader view: "Once the U.N., and
above all the American government, had adopted the goal of
unifying Korea, it set in motion the Chinese intervention.
MacArthur shared, no doubt, in the making of a flawed policy,
but he did not initiate or determine it."
   But most often the authors come back to their theory that
we should seek the causes of defeat in the characteristics of
military organization, the climate in which it must work, its
all too frequent emphasis on lessons from past wars, and
inherent structural rigidities.
   This does not really explain why some military forces win
and some lose -- but adaptability, ingenuity, the flexibility
derived from living in free societies (although dictatorships
do win from time to time), and finally the will to win can
overcome structural organizational problems.
   Messrs. Cohen and Gooch have done their job well. They
have mastered their sources, used considerable imagination in
choosing campaigns to study, and developed criteria and
original theories to explain the outcome of the battles
chosen for study.
   Also, despite occasional irregularities of style of
presentation, the book is well-written and generally sound in
judgment. I would quarrel most notably with their view that
it was the French First Army that saved the British at
Dunkirk -- rather than the British Expeditionary Force itself
and the hastily assembled evacuation fleet. Also, I do not
believe the authors attach enough importance to the failure
of democracies to support their military in peacetime, and
the consequent haste and waste inevitably involved in trying
in a few months to make up for years of neglect.
   Still, these are minor quibbles with a book that ably
describes "the problem of command in the age of large and
complicated organizations." It will, I hope, be carefully
studied in schools that prepare our future leaders for battle
and command.
   ---
   Mr. Weinberger, who served as Secretary of Defense in the
Reagan White House, now is the publisher of Forbes magazine
and counsel to the law firm of Rogers &amp; Wells.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
