<HL>
   Moscow Confronts National Symbol
   In Its Efforts to Raise Bread Prices
   ----
   By Elisabeth Rubinfien
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- It's best not to tinker with the soul of Russia,
as the Soviet government is finding out.
   The Supreme Soviet, the Soviet parliament, overwhelmingly
rejected government plans to raise bread prices July 1,
postponing discussion of the matter until September. In doing
so, it extended a long list of genuflections to bread as a
symbol in Russian life.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bread has been called the father of Russia, the soul of
Russia, the thing without which life means nothing. When a
valued guest visits a Soviet home, he is offered bread and
salt as a traditional welcome. Some schools hold special
"Bread Cult" evenings to introduce children to the history
and cultural significance of bread.
   "We teach that we were very rich, and there was beautiful
delicious bread, fresh every day," says a former Moscow
schoolteacher. "It was meant to be a description of the whole
Russian character."
   Leningrad has a Bread Museum, and every citizen well knows
that in the 900-day siege of Leningrad during World War II,
Leningraders were rationed to 100 grams of bread a day, and
the bread was made of flour and sawdust. Even the Bolsheviks
invoked bread in their rallying cry for the revolution:
"Land, bread and peace."
   As a result, the price of bread has hardly risen in the
70-plus years since then. The last price rise was in 1962. At
a Moscow bakery today, a long white loaf sells for about 20
kopeks (32 cents at the official exchange rate) and a dark
round for 10 kopeks.
   The government says it's high time to change. President
Mikhail Gorbachev complains that bread is so inexpensive
children play football with it. But when Prime Minister
Nikolai Ryzhkov last month proposed tripling bread prices as
part of his economic reform program, it caused a storm of
criticism.
   Opposition to the program within the Parliament was
particularly strong from the Central Asian regions, where
grain makes up a large proportion of the diet. And in the
breadbaskets of the Soviet Union -- the Ukraine and
Byelorussia -- local Parliaments said they would refuse to
comply with the price increase.
   But the average shopper seems to have accepted reality
over myth more quickly than the average Parliament member.
"Bread must be taken care of, but it doesn't matter if they
increase the price several times because it's way too cheap,"
said Nina, a middle-aged shopper at the largest bakery in
Moscow, where the walls are decorated with posters
proclaiming, "Bread is Precious."
   By subsidizing the bread price, the government had worked
itself into its present conundrum. Although farmers grow far
more food grain than fodder, the Soviet Union in 1989
imported 36 million tons of grain to fill about 40% of their
needs. Bread is so cheap that farmers feed it to their pigs.
   The government raised wholesale prices for grain in April
as a production incentive to try to reduce the dependence on
imports. They assumed that it would be able to offset some of
the cost by raising retail prices. Now, says Deputy Prime
Minister Leonid Abalkin, the government will have to pay out
an extra nine billion rubles this year to make up the
shortfall. A ruble is worth $1.67 at the official exchange
rate, but only a fraction of that in the black market.
   The vote to postpone discussion of bread price increases
until September may only add to public frustration. "At least
if the price goes up, maybe the quality will be better," says
Larisa Vesuchkina, as she prods loaves on a bakery shop's
shelves with the customary small metal spatula. "These days
it only lasts a day or two and we have to throw it out."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0128
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0128.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Brady Says S&amp;L Bailout Cost Expected
   To Increase by as Much as $50 Billion
   ----
   By Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, saying
that a further $30 billion to $50 billion will be needed for
the thrift bailout next year, encountered escalating
criticism from Democrats who think the Bush administration is
mishandling the cleanup.
   Mr. Brady, who recently estimated that the cost of the
bailout -- excluding interest -- probably will more than
double to over $130 billion, also said that without new cash,
the bailout effort will be out of money by the end of this
year. He didn't say how much additional funding will be
needed in the October-December quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Depressed real estate markets, higher interest rates,
thrifts' losses in the junk-bond market and a tepid response
from potential buyers of sick thrifts all have contributed to
the higher costs, Mr. Brady said. "Let's face it, and get on
with the job," he urged the committee.
   But Democrats took the occasion to draw a distinction
between how the thrift crisis developed, for which both
parties appear culpable, and the halting progress in carrying
out the massive thrift law, for which the lawmakers held the
administration responsible. Their comments were the latest
Democratic effort to capitalize on a growing problem for
President Bush.
   "There's a second S&amp;L crisis that started Aug. 9," when
the law passed, said Rep. Charles Schumer (D., N.Y.). "We
have heard more from the president about broccoli than we
have heard about this crisis." Rep. Richard Neal (D., Mass.)
said: "We are sitting on a volcano of public opinion on this
issue."
   Members admonished the administration for its original,
low cost estimates, saying that interest-rate projections
were particularly low. They also complained that the
administration should have foreseen that there would be few
buyers for thrifts under the new law's restrictions on their
activities. "I think the appearance to the American public is
that this is floundering," said Rep. Bruce Vento (D., Minn.),
who chairs a task force on the efforts.
   Originally, the administration targeted $50 billion to
cover current S&amp;L losses. Yesterday, Mr. Brady said about
$28.3 billion will have been spent by June 30. At that point,
the administration expects 289 insolvent thrifts to have been
liquidated or sold, but their bad investments will remain in
the hands of the government. Moreover, about 800 more thrifts
are expected to require similar action.
   Mr. Brady didn't specifically ask for Congress to pass
legislation to raise the additional cash, saying this is
likely to be determined in the current budget meetings
between the administration and Congress.
   For its part, the administration used the hearing to call
again for a cut in the tax on capital gains, as a way to
bolster the real estate market. "At the margin, I think it's
the single most important thing we can do," said Housing and
Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp, who is a member of the
Oversight Board monitoring the thrift cleanup.
   He also said that a clampdown on credit has made it
tougher to sell the repossessed real estate. "I have the
feeling that there is a strong impression among people
involved in real estate and housing that there is a crunch in
the supply of credit," said Mr. Kemp.
   Mr. Kemp also cautioned that politicizing the S&amp;L mess
could slow the progress even more. "If we turn this into an
issue of who and when and just exactly which party, I think
it's going to be a serious blow to the necessity of finding
some area of cooperation," he said.
   Both parties are pursuing S&amp;L fraud legislation more
aggressively. Sen. Joseph Biden (D., Del.), chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee, announced he will hold a hearing
next month to examine many of the proposals to crack down on
fraud, and said he will introduce a comprehensive S&amp;L fraud
bill after the hearing. House Banking Committee Chairman
Henry Gonzalez (D., Texas) and the committee's ranking
Republican, Ohio Rep. Chalmers Wylie are also introducing a
bill to speed S&amp;L-related prosecution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
