<HL>
   Sweden's Consumer Prices Rise
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   STOCKHOLM -- Sweden's consumer prices in May rose 0.6%
from April and 10.2% from a year earlier, Statistics Sweden,
the national statistics agency, said, citing mainly alcohol,
tobacco and food price increases.
   Consumer prices shot up 7% in the first five months of
this year, the agency said, and 2.9 percentage points of the
increase resulted from the major tax overhaul being gradually
introduced.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sweden's annualized rate of inflation rose to 10.2% in May
from 10.1% in April, and was up from the 6.6% rate registered
in May last year.
   The national Price and Competition Office predicted
consumer prices will increase at a rate of 10% this year.
   Sweden's consumer price index, based on 1980 prices
equalling 100, was measured at 206.4 in May, up from 205.2 in
April.
</TEXT>
