<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   After 111, the Deluge?
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<LP>
   It has taken less than a week after Californians voted
narrowly to raise the gasoline tax with Prop. 111 for the
state's top Democrats to go whole-hog on taxes. As the
cornerstone of a $2.3 billion tax package (the Gann spending
limit won't allow any more than that), the Democratic
chairmen of the Legislature's fiscal committees want to raise
the upper income-tax bracket to 11% from 9.3%. Apparently,
revenue growth of 7% annually hasn't kept pace with spending,
so there's a big deficit and the liberal reflex is to try to
soak many of the state's most productive residents further.
Even after Prop. 111's win, however, the Big Democratic Tax
Sponge may find California a pretty dry state.
   {See related story: "REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) --
Asides: Tax Revolt Note" -- WSJ June 15, 1990}
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0079
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0079.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Tax Revolt Note
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<LP>
   Meanwhile, a small piece of evidence has emerged to
challenge Prop. 111's supposed lesson that voters will
approve a tax if they know it will go for a specific program.
This week North Dakotans voted 59% against a temporary,
one-cent sales-tax increase to fund schools. Earmarking the
money for education didn't help -- last December North
Dakotans turned down a non-earmarked sales-tax hike by a
narrower 53% margin. The real lesson may be that voters won't
support tax increases for programs that they are convinced
fail to deliver value for money.
   {See related story: "REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) --
Asides: After 111, the Deluge?" -- WSJ June 15, 1990}
</LP>
