<HL>
   California Agency
   Tightens Standard
   On Vehicle Emissions
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- The California Air Resources Board,
continuing its campaign to attempt to force auto makers to
improve pollution controls, adopted tighter tailpipe emission
standards for light trucks, vans and certain other large
vehicles.
   Under the new standards, the board said up to 150,000
vehicles a year would be equipped with anti-smog equipment
similar to that on passenger cars. Currently, larger vehicles
don't normally feature some of the more advanced
anti-pollution technology required on passenger cars.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The standards will be phased in over the 1995 and 1996
model years. The board said the new standards would reduce
emissions from the targeted vehicles by 26% to 75%, depending
on the model and its size. Vehicles covered by the new
standards range in weight from 3,750 pounds to 14,000 pounds,
and would include ambulances, tow trucks, small motor homes
and oversized pickup trucks.
   The agency estimated that it would cost $61 to $390 a
vehicle to make modifications needed to meet the new
standards.
   Manufacturers of the affected vehicles couldn't be reached
to comment. In general, however, car makers and gasoline
producers have said that the board's pollution goals are
unreachable or economically unfeasible.
   The new standards are in keeping with the board's recent
drive to adopt tough new emission standards. The campaign has
national significance because California is the country's
biggest car market and because many states model pollution
laws on California's.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0066
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0066.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Brazil Cannot Meet All
   Debt Interest Due in '90
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   RIO DE JANEIRO (AP) -- Brazil's top debt negotiator said
the government cannot pay all the interest on its foreign
debt this year because of a lack of foreign currency
reserves, a major newspaper reported.
   Chief negotiator Jorio Dauster said Brazil would be able
to pay only about $5 billion of the $15 billion in interest
owed to private foreign banks in 1990 without using up its
foreign reserves, the Rio daily Jornal do Brasil reported.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Everyone knows Brazil doesn't have the kind of money to
pay this interest," the negotiator told the newspaper.
   Brazil hasn't paid interest to private creditors on its
foreign debt since September and now is $5.6 billion in
arrears, although it has kept up interest payments to
European government lenders.
   The suspension of interest payments is intended to keep
Brazil's foreign reserves from falling below $6 billion, the
equivalent of six months of imports. Foreign reserves stand
at about $7 billion, according to the central bank.
   The negotiator said the government first wanted to
negotiate a standby pact with the International Monetary Fund
for a $2 billion bridge loan before resuming talks on back
interest payments.
   An agreement with the IMF is considered crucial to
Brazil's plans to renegotiate its $114 billion foreign debt,
the Third World's largest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Southland Corp.
   Sweetens Offer
   To Bondholders
   ---
   Thompson Stake Reduced
   Under Proposal Backed
   By Japanese Investors
   ----
   By Andy Zipser
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   SLCPC IYCOY J.SEV
</CO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- With its rescue by Japanese investors in
jeopardy, debt-mired Southland Corp. said it has sweetened
its proposed exchange offer to bondholders by an estimated
$200 million after weeks of intense negotiations.
   The new proposal, which was greeted with "tentative
optimism," according to one bond analyst, also would sharply
reduce the equity stake to be retained by the Thompson
family, which founded the giant convenience-store chain. More
importantly, if accepted by bondholders, it should enable the
operator of 7-Eleven stores to skirt a bankruptcy-court
filing. The proposal has been approved by Ito-Yokado Co. and
Seven-Eleven Japan Co., which have agreed to buy a 75% stake
in Southland if the company can restructure its $1.8 billion
in publicly traded debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Southland also announced it won't pay $69 million in
interest due in cash today on two of its debt issues, as well
as additional pay-in-kind interest due on another issue, in
an effort to increase liquidity. That leaves it with a 30-day
grace period before it defaults, but with a new offer on the
table, bondholders seemed unperturbed.
   "They've made a significant move from their previous
position," said George Varughese, managing director of
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., which has been advising the
bondholders.
   Under the revised exchange offer, bondholders would
receive debt securities totaling about $550 million, bearing
cash interest at rates of 12% to 14% and having maturities of
six to seven years. The original proposal called for
zero-coupon notes, which don't pay interest but increase in
value over time, and maturities of more than 10 years. A
Southland spokesman wouldn't disclose the amount of
zero-coupon notes offered in the original proposal.
   The new proposal also slices up the Southland pie into
significantly different chunks, with bondholders and
preferred shareholders receiving approximately 18.5% of the
common stock, up from about 10% in the initial swap offer.
The equity position of the Thompson family and their capital
partners would be reduced to 6.5% from the 15% they would
have gotten in the first proposal. Part of bondholders'
opposition to the original offer stemmed from the sizable
equity stake retained by the Thompsons, who founded the
company as a chain of ice stores in the 1920s.
   John Gordon of Deltec Securities Corp., who has headed the
steering committee of Southland's security holders, said the
new proposal was the result of "intense discussion in which
we were dealing with questions of how pain will be
distributed." Although some sticking points remain --
principally over apportionment of value -- a final agreement
could be in place by early next week, he added.
   Anticipating such an agreement, Southland and its
prospective Japanese investors have agreed to extend their
stock purchase agreement, which was scheduled to expire
yesterday, to Aug. 15.
   Southland, which owns about 6,700 7-Eleven and other
convenience stores in the U.S. and Canada, went private in a
$4.9 billion leveraged buy-out in late 1987 to avoid a
possible hostile bid by the Belzberg family of Canada. But
increased competition has eroded sales and profit margins,
and made it difficult for the company to service the huge
debt it took on in going private.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
