<HL>
   Your Money Matters:
   New Breed of Financial Sharks Feeds on Investor Fears
   ----
   By Ellen E. Schultz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   When it comes to investment scams, it's fear, not greed,
that gets most people into trouble.
   Take Mary Lou Butler, a 59-year-old Phoenix, Ariz., woman,
who says she was worried about her financial security. "I was
looking for a financial planner who could take the insurance
money -- $130,000 -- I got when my husband died, and invest
it for a monthly income," she says.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The "planner" she found was Dwight Edward Depottey, who
said he would put the money into a "low-risk" investment.
Instead, Mr. Depottey used at least part of it for his own
business and personal benefit, says Margaret Ellis, an
investigator with the securities division of the Arizona
Corporation Commission.
   Last month, Mr. Depottey pleaded guilty to one count of
"conspiracy to commit fraudulent schemes" and no-contest to
one count of theft following an indictment charging that he
defrauded dozens of investors. Most of his victims lost
everything they had invested, says Ms. Ellis. Mr. Depottey is
scheduled for sentencing in state superior court in Phoenix
next Tuesday. His attorney, Leonard G. Brown, had no comment.
   State securities regulators and others say a growing
number of crooks are exploiting individuals' worries about
their financial futures to sell bogus investments and
worthless counseling.
   "They're going after people who are saving for retirement
and their kids' education," says Rep. Rick Boucher, who has
introduced a bill calling for stricter regulation of the
financial planning industry. "These aren't people who want to
do high-risk securities," says the Virginia Democrat,
"they're people who have $400 a month they want to put away."
   A poll released yesterday by the International Association
for Financial Planning, a trade group, shows that most
Americans are "overwhelmingly pessimistic" about their
personal finances: 86% said that college costs have risen
beyond the reach of most families, and 66% said there is less
chance for retirees to be self-sufficient in the coming
decade.
   Those are the kinds of worries that lead people to turn to
a financial planner. But instead of legitimate professionals,
many individuals end up putting themselves in the hands of
charlatans.
   "They present all these statistics about what it's going
to cost for education and retirement, then sell you
anything," says Rep. Boucher.
   "Yes, there are certainly frauds out there," says Robert
A. Hewitt, chairman of the IAFP. But "in spite of some of the
sensational headlines, most fraud and abuse was perpetrated
not by financial planners, but by frauds posing as financial
planners."
   Securities regulators say they're noticing an increase in
the number of specifically targeted pitches.
   Gerald Lewis, Florida's comptroller, says he has always
seen plenty of scams that target retirees. But lately, he
says, more and more schemes are tied to college investments.
   "I see ads that say things like, `How to Prepare for Your
Children's Education.' Just because you see an ad like that
doesn't mean something is wrong, but we're seeing evidence
that people are being victimized by those types of comeons,"
Mr. Lewis says.
   Missouri Commissioner of Securities John Perkins says that
law-enforcement people in his state headed off a
college-investment scheme last year when they arrested Robert
J. Recklein, an unregistered financial planner who was later
sentenced to 15 years for securities violations connected
with the sale of phony promissory notes to people who sought
his financial advice.
   When they searched Mr. Recklein's office, regulators found
what they believe is a marketing plan they say he was
intending to use to sell phony college investments. Among
those listed in the plan as "targets" were grandparents of
newborns, who "often give generously," and parents who "have
repaid their own college loans."
   The plan's "strategy" called for "establishing Robert J.
Recklein as a knowledgeable, inventive and dependable
leader," according to the papers found in his office. It
included procedures that any marketing plan might employ,
including participating in radio talk shows, sending mailings
to day-care centers and to senior citizens.
   Mr. Recklein's lawyer, Dale Myers, says that his client's
investments were "nothing more than Ponzi operations," and
that his client could have been sentenced to only two years,
except that "he stole additional money from investors" while
he was out on bail. As for his client's plan to sell college
investments modeled as prepaid tuition plans, he says Mr.
Recklein got the idea from reading about a legitimate program
run by the state of Michigan.
   "Crooks use the same marketing and sales techniques that
the legitimate financial planning professionals use, which is
why they're so camouflaged," says Scott Stapf of the North
American Securities Administrators Association.
   "Crooked planners will work through community
organizations, unions and church groups, and will make
presentations. Afterwards, they get lists of members and move
in with sales pitches," says Mr. Stapf. "It's a very
effective way to set up people, because they trust the
planner, and feel guilty about having gotten the `free
advice.'"
   For example, in Barrington, Ill., radio ads touted a
series of "no-cost, no-obligation financial planning
seminars" to help people plan for and save for retirement.
One script read: ". . . We have never seen people so
bewildered and confused, especially persons who would like to
plan retirement, as well as those already retired. The
horrors of Wall Street, the scary bond market, fluctuating
interest rates, they are all reasons for concern."
   People who attended the classes were then invited to
participate in a personal financial planning consultation,
where many were sold limited partnerships purportedly earning
"guaranteed" annual interest of 10% to 15%. The two men
involved, Earl Dean Gordon and Kenneth F. Boula,
"acknowledged that they participated in conduct that
ultimately involved $5 million in funds obtained from
investors in real estate limited partnerships where
misrepresentations were made to investors," says their
attorney, David Stetler.
   Both pleaded guilty in federal court to mail-fraud
charges, and are scheduled to be sentenced today in U.S.
district court in Chicago.
   Law-enforcement officials and securities regulators say
many people are lulled into thinking fraud can't happen to
them because they aren't the stereotypically "greedy"
investor. But, says Susan Bryant, the Oklahoma commissioner
of securities: "This is not based on (investor) greed, and
that's one of the reasons this is frightening."
   ---
              How To Get Help Spotting a Crook
                                                                                                       

   Investors can reduce their chances of falling prey to a
charlatan by checking the backgrounds of financial planners
and other investment professionals with their state's
securities office. Find out who to call by phoning the North
American Securities Administrators Association in Washington
(202-737-0900).
                                                                                                       

   Here's what to ask:
                                                                                                       

   -- Is planner registered to sell investments in your
state, and, if so, what investments?
   -- Does the planner have a record of disciplinary actions
taken by state securities agencies, the Securities and
Exchange Commission or self-regulatory organizations such as
the National Association of Securities Dealers?
   -- Has the planner been sued by clients, and, if so, what
did the complaints allege and what was the outcome?
   -- Has the planner filed for bankruptcy, or been
prosecuted for a money crime?
   -- Does the planner have the educational background and
work history he or she claims?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0059
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0059.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Police May Use Checkpoints in Efforts
   To Catch Drunken Drivers, Justices Say
   ----
   By Stephen Wermiel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   TX GM
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Supreme Court ruled that police may set
up highway checkpoints in efforts to catch drunken drivers.
   By a 6-3 vote, the high court said checkpoints in which
police stop every car don't violate the Fourth Amendment's
protection against "unreasonable searches and seizures." In
an opinion written by Chief Justice William Rehnquist, the
court upheld a checkpoint set up in 1986 by the Michigan
State Police.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Use of checkpoints by state and local police has become
widespread in recent years as public attention on drunken
driving has heightened. Alcohol played a part in more than
23,000 traffic deaths in 1988 of a total of 47,000 traffic
fatalities, according to Transportation Department
statistics.
   Estimates of checkpoint use vary. The National Commission
Against Drunk Driving, a private group, said several years
ago that police have used checkpoints in all 50 states and
the District of Columbia. But some state and federal
officials say the number of states using the checkpoints is
lower. A 1985 survey by Michigan officials found 36 states
using checkpoints. Thirty-one states filed a
friend-of-the-court brief in support of Michigan in the high
court.
   The high court said that stopping a car at a checkpoint
falls within the legal definition of a "seizure," triggering
the protection of the Fourth Amendment. But the court
concluded that such a seizure isn't "unreasonable" for three
reasons: The states have a strong interest in curbing drunken
driving; checkpoints help achieve that aim, and the intrusion
on motorists is "slight."
   The ruling is the culmination of a decade of legal
uncertainty created by an earlier high court ruling. In 1979,
the justices struck down a Delaware system of establishing
checkpoints and randomly selecting cars to be checked. The
court said random selection gave police officers too much
discretion without standards for exercising their authority.
"Questioning of all oncoming traffic at roadblock-type stops
is one possible alternative," the court suggested as an aside
in 1979.
   Since then, according to Mothers Against Drunk Driving,
which hailed yesterday's decision, courts in 21 states have
upheld checkpoints while judges in 12 others have struck them
down. In Michigan, a state appeals court ruled that the
checkpoint, which was used on only one night, violated the
Fourth Amendment.
   Yesterday's ruling should eliminate any uncertainty,
although in some states the checkpoints may still violate
privacy guarantees in state constitutions that are broader
than the Fourth Amendment.
   Justice John Stevens dissented, joined by Justices William
Brennan and Thurgood Marshall. Challenging the majority's
conclusions, the dissenters said there isn't any evidence to
demonstrate that checkpoints are more effective than using
the same police manpower for traffic patrols.
   And in an unusual and pointed reference to totalitarian
governments, the dissenters said: "Unannounced investigatory
seizures are, particularly when they take place at night, the
hallmark of regimes far different from ours." They also said
that alcohol use has been declining as a cause of traffic
fatalities for the past six years. (Michigan State Police
Department vs. Sitz)
                                                                                                       

   Discounts for Wholesalers
                                                                                                       

   The justices gave manufacturers more flexibility to charge
lower prices to wholesale distributors than to retailers in
the same market, as long as the discount is reasonably based
on services provided by the wholesalers.
   But while establishing this flexibility, the justices
upheld a $1,349,700 jury verdict against Texaco Inc. for
illegal price discrimination against a dozen retail gasoline
dealers in the Spokane, Wash., area. In an opinion written by
Justice Stevens, the high court said the evidence showed that
Texaco's discounts to two wholesalers in Spokane weren't
related to any services performed by the companies.
   The vote was 9-0 to uphold the verdict against Texaco and
6-3 to allow manufacturers to offer so-called reasonable
"functional discounts" to wholesalers but to deny them to
retailers.
   Functional discounts are price reductions offered
generally to wholesalers for services they provide to
retailers that the manufacturer might otherwise have to
provide directly.
   The Robinson-Patman Act, added by Congress to federal
antitrust law in 1936, generally makes it illegal to
discriminate in prices charged to different purchasers when
the effect is to reduce competition. However, the court
recognized that some functional discounts, although a form of
price discrimination, don't violate federal law.
   Peter Fishbein, a New York lawyer who represented Texaco
in the high court, said the decision "is very significant"
and "makes it possible for suppliers to have dual
distribution systems of wholesalers and retailers and to
charge different prices to each." The ruling could affect a
range of manufacturing and production industries, from
gasoline and oil to auto parts.
   In the Texaco case, the jury found in 1985, and a federal
appeals court in San Francisco agreed in 1988, that Texaco
violated federal law by giving a discount on gasoline to two
Spokane-area wholesalers. The wholesalers had a dual role,
distributing the gasoline to retailers and selling some of it
through their own retail outlets that competed directly with
independent Texaco retailers. The jury found that Texaco
discriminated because the wholesalers' retail outlets
received the discount while other retailers didn't.
   The jury awarded the retail dealers $449,900, which was
tripled under federal law to $1,349,700.
   Justice Byron White, in one separate opinion, and Justice
Antonin Scalia, joined by Justice Anthony Kennedy, in another
opinion, disagreed with the court's exception to the law for
"reasonable functional discounts." (Texaco Inc. vs.
Hasbrouck)
                                                                                                       

   Clean Air Plans
                                                                                                       

   The justices ruled that the Environmental Protection
Agency's failure to review a state's proposed changes in a
clean-air plan within a four-month deadline doesn't mean the
changes automatically take effect and the old standards can
no longer be enforced.
   The ruling is a defeat for General Motors Corp., which was
sued by the EPA in 1987 for failing to comply with
Massachusetts clean-air standards adopted in 1980.
Massachusetts had already proposed changes in its plan that
gave GM more time to comply.
   The Clean Air Act says the EPA should approve or reject
plan changes within four months. A federal judge dismissed
the EPA's lawsuit, ruling that the four months had lapsed,
that the plan changes were already in effect, and that the
EPA could no longer enforce the old standards. A federal
appeals court in Boston reversed the decision and said the
expiration of the four-month limit didn't bar the EPA from
enforcing the old standards.
   In an opinion written by Justice Harry Blackmun, the high
court affirmed the appeals court ruling in favor of the EPA.
But the impact may be short-lived if Congress agrees on a new
Clean Air Act. (General Motors Corp. vs. U.S.)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
