<HL>
   Business Brief -- Greater New York Savings Bank:
   Board Adopts Rights Plan
   To Block Hostile Takeovers
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   GRTR
</CO>
<LP>
   Greater New York Savings Bank, New York, said its board
adopted a shareholder rights plan to prevent a hostile
takeover.
   The rights plan goes into effect if a holder acquires 20%
or more of Greater New York's shares, and would entitle other
holders to purchase common with a value of twice the right's
exercise price.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a letter to shareholders, Charles J. Ohlig, chairman of
the thrift, said the plan isn't intended to prevent an
acquisition on terms that are favorable to all shareholders.
   Greater New York last year adopted a leveraged employee
stock ownership plan to increase the cost of an unwanted
takeover proposal by Emigrant Savings Bank. Greater New York,
with assets of $3 billion and deposits of $2.2 billion, has
offices in the metropolitan area.
   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Greater
New York shares closed at $6.375, down 37.5 cents.
</TEXT>
