<HL>
   Additional Taxes
   Are Sought by IRS
   From Japanese Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES MC J.TOS HIT SNE
</CO>
<GV>
INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)
</GV>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- At least one major Japanese electronics company
has received a request from the U.S. Internal Revenue Service
to pay additional taxes, and others are expecting similar
notice soon.
   The U.S. government has long alleged that Japanese
companies are avoiding U.S. taxes by charging their
subsidiaries too much for certain goods, such as
semiconductors and videocassette recorders -- an action that
depresses the stated profits of the American units.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. has received a request,
and is "cooperating" with the U.S. government, according to
an official company statement. The company added, however,
that no bilateral standard exists for "transfer prices" and
that the matter was still under discussion between the U.S.
and Japanese governments. A spokesman refused to disclose the
amount of the tax request, or when it was made.
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, in Friday's editions, reported
that Matsushita was asked to pay an added 10 billion yen
($64.6 million) in taxes; Toshiba Corp. was asked to pay 30
billion yen more, and Hitachi Ltd. 10 billion yen more.
   The Matsushita spokesman said the figure reported for that
company was "too high." Toshiba officials said they hadn't
yet received any official request, but that they have been
under investigation by the IRS for transfer pricing questions
since 1985. A Hitachi spokesman said the company has been
under investigation since 1986, but that it hadn't received
any requests for additional taxes.
   Sony Corp. said it had received requests for additional
information to the IRS about a month ago, and is still
working to supply the requested material.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900615-0016
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900615-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   SCEcorp Unit Ends
   Contract for Work
   On Three Power Plants
</HL>
<DATE>
06/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   SCE CE
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   IRVINE, Calif. -- Mission Power Engineering Co., a unit of
SCEcorp., said it terminated its contract for the engineering
and construction of three geothermal power generating plants
in the Coso and China Lake areas of California, which are
owned and operated by California Energy Co., San Francisco.
   "We've just walked off the job," said Jack Adrian, Mission
Power's president and chief executive officer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The termination of the contract follows Mission Power's
filing of a lawsuit on June 5 against California Energy and
its partners in the $300 million-plus project. The complaint,
filed in state court in Inyo County, accuses California
Energy of making changes in the scope of the work, triggering
serious delays, and refusing to pay for additional costs.
   Mission Power is seeking more than $79 million in the
action, plus interest and damages for alleged fraud and
misrepresentation by California Energy.
   Michael Heys, California Energy's president, maintained
yesterday that his company has appropriately compensated
Mission Power. "There is nothing due on contractural work,"
he said. "In fact, there has been an overpayment of
$170,000."
   Mr. Heys added that the power plants at the center of the
dispute are "substantially complete" and, therefore, Mission
Power's walkout will not cause "an interruption of
operations."
</TEXT>
